candidates.title: Timothy J. Berners-Lee
candidates.details: Founder of the internet

candidates.title: Alan Turing
candidates.details: A brilliant British mathematician who took a leading role in breaking Nazi ciphers during WWII. In his seminal 1936 paper, he proved that there cannot exist any universal algorithmic method of determining truth in mathematics, and that mathematics will always contain undecidable propositions. His work is widely acknowledged as foundational research of computer science and artificial intelligence.

candidates.title: John von Neumann
candidates.details: A polymath and pioneer of the application of operator theory to quantum mechanics, in the development of functional analysis. Along with fellow physicists Edward Teller and Stanislaw Ulam, von Neumann worked out key steps in the nuclear physics involving thermonuclear reactions and the hydrogen bomb.

candidates.title: Alan Kay
candidates.details: Known for his work on object-oriented programming languages and graphical user interfaces

candidates.title: Ada Lovelace
candidates.details: Often referred to as the world’s first computer programmer. Her work helped lay the groundwork for modern-day programming.

candidates.title: Charles Babbage
candidates.details: The “father of the computer,” invented the prototype of the world’s first mechanical calculator, the Difference Engine. With the help of mathematician Ada Lovelace, he also created the Analytical Engine, the first general-purpose computer and a precursor of the modern computer, with its looping and sequential mechanism.

candidates.title: Claude Shannon
candidates.details: An electrical engineer, mathematician, and cryptographer. Shannon is considered the father of information theory. He is also credited with founding digital circuit design theory.

candidates.title: Dennis Ritchie
candidates.details: Worked at Bell Labs Computing Sciences Research Center for most of his career, co-developing the Unix operating system and B programming language with Kenneth Thompson, co-winning the 1983 A.M. Turing Award for it. Earlier, he had also created C programming language.

candidates.title: John McCarthy
candidates.details: American mathematician and computer scientist who was a pioneer in the field of artificial intelligence (AI), developed Lisp, and invented garbage collection. His main research in the field involved the formalization of commonsense knowledge.

candidates.title: Vitalik Buterin
candidates.details: A Canadian programmer and writer who is best known as one of the co-founders of Ethereum. Buterin became involved with cryptocurrency early in its inception, co-founding Bitcoin Magazine in 2011.

candidates.title: Clifford Stoll
candidates.details: An American astronomer, author and teacher. He is best known for his investigation in 1986, while working as a systems administrator, that led to the capture of hacker Markus Hess, and for Stoll's subsequent book The Cuckoo's Egg, in which he details the investigation.

candidates.title: Ken Thompson
candidates.details: An American pioneer of computer science. Thompson worked at Bell Labs for most of his career where he designed and implemented the original Unix operating system. He also invented the B programming language, the direct predecessor to the C programming language. Since 2006, Thompson has worked at Google, where he co-developed the Go programming language.

candidates.title: Shafi Goldwasser
candidates.details: The RSA Professor of Electrical Engineering and Computer Science at MIT. Invented zero-knowledge proofs.

candidates.title: Margaret Hamilton
candidates.details: Hamilton has published more than 130 papers, proceedings, and reports, about sixty projects, and six major programs. She is one of the people credited with coining the term "software engineering"

candidates.title: Martin Hellman
candidates.details: Introduced the ideas of public-key cryptography and digital signatures, the foundation for security protocols on the Internet today.

candidates.title: Linus Torvalds
candidates.details: Created the first version of the Linux kernel.

candidates.title: Bob Kahn
candidates.details: Designed the Transmission Control Protocol and Internet Protocol.

candidates.title: Richard Hamming
candidates.details: Created the fields of error-correcting code, Hamming code, Hamming matrix, the Hamming window, Hamming numbers, sphere-packing, and the Hamming distance.

candidates.title: James Cooley
candidates.details: Created the fast Fourier transform.

candidates.title: Wesley A. Clark
candidates.details: An American physicist who is credited for designing the first modern personal computer
